        <h2 id="vs-related">Content outline vs content brief - which comes first</h2>
        <p>The outline is the answer to "how should the piece be structured?" The brief is the answer to "why are we writing it at all?" Both matter, but they work in sequence.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Content brief</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Strategic context: audience, goal, competitors</li>
              <li>Tone, voice, and brand guidelines</li>
              <li>Target keyword and secondary terms</li>
              <li>Deadline, word count, format</li>
              <li>Written by the editor/strategist</li>
              <li>Comes first - before the outline</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Content outline</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Structural blueprint: every H2 and H3</li>
              <li>Bullet points per section</li>
              <li>Required data, examples, and links</li>
              <li>Word count per section</li>
              <li>Written by the writer or an outliner</li>
              <li>Comes after the brief, before drafting</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for content outlines</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Analyse the top 10 SERP results first.</strong> Note format, word count, common H2s, and unique angles before you draft a single heading.</li>
          <li><strong>Match dominant intent, then differentiate.</strong> If 8 of 10 top results are listicles, publish a listicle - but include one section none of them cover.</li>
          <li><strong>Plan 3-5 internal links per outline.</strong> Note the exact anchor text and destination in the outline so writers do not skip them.</li>
          <li><strong>Set a word count target per section.</strong> "500 words" as a whole is vague. "H2 A: 200 words, H2 B: 300 words" is executable.</li>
          <li><strong>Include an FAQ with 4-6 PAA questions.</strong> Pull them from Google's People Also Ask box to earn FAQ-rich snippets.</li>
          <li><strong>Note obligatory data and quotes.</strong> If a stat or expert quote is critical, write it into the outline. Writers should not have to guess what to research.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake - outlining without SERP analysis</div>
          <p>Writers who outline from imagination produce pieces that look right but never rank. Every outline should start with a live SERP scan - what Google currently rewards for that query is the baseline your outline must beat.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common content outline mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Skipping SERP analysis.</strong> Outlines built without checking the top 10 rank poorly.</li>
          <li><strong>Missing the dominant format.</strong> Publishing a guide when Google rewards listicles for that query.</li>
          <li><strong>No word-count targets per section.</strong> Writers over-index on early sections and skimp on the ones that convert.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring internal links.</strong> Every outline should specify 3-5 internal links with anchor text.</li>
          <li><strong>Vague sub-points.</strong> "Cover pricing" is not enough. "List the 3 tiers with per-user pricing" is.</li>
          <li><strong>Inconsistent format across writers.</strong> Every outline should follow the same template so quality stays predictable.</li>
        </ul>

